[Event "How to Create Original Openings: Using Databases"]
[Date "2017.04.08"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "C44"]
[Opening "King's Knight Opening: Normal Variation"]
[StudyName "How to Create Original Openings"]
[ChapterName "Using Databases"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/W9cOy7mY/6mVvKuCI"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/DrHack"]
[UTCDate "2017.04.08"]
[UTCTime "22:48:01"]

1. e4 { You want to surprise somebody with a new opening idea, but think there is nothing new in chess? } 1... e5 { That's just not true, as this study will show. I hope you know enough to do your own opening work by the end of this study. } 2. Nf3 { Go ahead and open your favorite database as we get started: If you don't have one, use one of the many online free databases. Search google for chessbase database or visit "database.chessbase.com" to use my favorite. } 2... Nc6 { This position has been played hundreds of thousands of times, I'm sure your database will tell you the same. If you are hoping to become an expert or master chess player, one of the many main lines - the moves that show up as the most played and most successful - might be your choice. } 3. b3 { However, if you are interested in original chess, the less popular moves can provide a blank canvas to work on, a move like 3. b3 may be your choice. You'll see in your database that this is not a very popular move. } 3... Nf6 { From here, you will need a computer program like stockfish to help you analyze your ideas. Stockfish is an open source chess engine that is free to download and use. With only a few games to draw from, a database will not offer enough game play to test the strongest middle game plans. We are on our own - Just like we wanted! } 4. Bb5 { By move 4, we are in original territory, and the computer agrees that the position is reasonably even. Any amateur can beat any other amateur as black or as white from a position like this. The game of chess, for all of us amateurs is richer than it has ever been in history. } *


[Event "How to Create Original Openings: Original Ideas In Common Openings"]
[Date "2017.04.08"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "C45"]
[Opening "Scotch Game: Mieses Variation"]
[StudyName "How to Create Original Openings"]
[ChapterName "Original Ideas In Common Openings"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/W9cOy7mY/EBt3sY75"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/DrHack"]
[UTCDate "2017.04.08"]
[UTCTime "23:03:09"]

1. e4 e5 2. d4 exd4 3. Nf3 Nc6 4. Nxd4 Nf6 { The scotch game is a fairly common opening. This position, whether you arrived here in a different move order or by this one, is a very popular position in the database. } 5. Nxc6 { Sometimes the one or two most common moves are the only moves that hold the status quo. Choosing a less popular move is choosing to be demolished. White could have chosen to defend his e4 pawn with a different move, but the choices were very limited. } 5... bxc6 6. e5 { In some positions, there are only one or two choices. We can not deviate at this moment without taking a significant disadvantage. This is not the moment for which we seek. Qe7 or Nd5. } 6... Qe7 7. Qe2 Nd5 8. c4 { We reach another very popular position with chess masters. Thousands of games have been played from here. } 8... Ba6 { Armed with our database, we can pick the least popular move at this moment, and arrive in original territory - being careful to check it with a computer to make sure black does not have a tactical victory. As long as the computer gives us an analysis between .25 and -.25, we are doing fine. } 9. h4 { Try it with your own openings. Search out a moment between move 5 and 10 where you can deviate from the most popular ideas. There are thousands of unexplored moves. } *


[Event "How to Create Original Openings: Studying New Territory"]
[Date "2017.04.08"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "B27"]
[Opening "Sicilian Defense: Hyperaccelerated Fianchetto"]
[StudyName "How to Create Original Openings"]
[ChapterName "Studying New Territory"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/W9cOy7mY/iF935Lxk"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/DrHack"]
[UTCDate "2017.04.08"]
[UTCTime "23:22:35"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 g6 { Let's take a look at an original position that can come up in the Sicilian dragon. } 3. d4 cxd4 4. Qxd4 { This is already a little off of the beaten track, but still played often enough to have plenty of examples. } 4... Nf6 5. Bb5 { When checking the database, white loses more often than he wins from this position. The problem is: the computer likes white! We've got our canvas to work with. } 5... a6 { In order to truly explore this position, we could just try a bunch of stuff, like a6, Nc6, Bb7, d6, and other moves. Maybe we could just play a lot of games from here and learn by practice. My favorite way to be introduced to a new position is to take the opposite side of it against stockfish set to it's hardest setting. Since I'm guaranteed to lose against stockfish in a position where I am clueless, it teaches me how to handle the various ideas that I have. } 6. e5 { In the end, its about familiarity with common tactical themes that can arise when we reach one of our original positions. We amateurs aren't going to remember 10 more moves of analysis from this position tomorrow, let alone a month from now, so maybe its best not to focus on doing so. } 6... axb5 (6... Nh5 7. e6 Bg7 8. exf7+ Kf8 9. Qa4 { In the end, we get to make a judgement call as to whether we would like to see a position like the one after 6. e5 again in a game. }) 7. exf6 Nc6 { Sargissian, Gabriel - Salgado Lopez, Ivan, 1-0, EU-ch 14th, 2013, https://lichess.org/Ngim3pAK } 8. Qh4 { In the end, we get to make a judgement call as to whether we would like to see the positions we might reach after 6.e5 in an actual game. } *


